    <activity xml:id="activity-discovering-function-rule">

        <introduction>
            <p>
                A function follows a rule that connects every input value to exactly one output value. 
                In this activity, you will investigate a pattern in a table of values and try to discover the function rule yourself.
            </p>
        </introduction>

        <task>
            <p>
                Study the table below carefully.
            </p>

            <tabular top="minor" bottom="minor">
                <row>
                    <cell><alert>Input <m>x</m></alert></cell>
                    <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>4</m></cell>
                </row>

                <row>
                    <cell><alert>Output <m>f(x)</m></alert></cell>
                    <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>5</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>7</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>9</m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Describe the pattern you observe in the output values.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    How is each output related to its corresponding input?
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Write a function rule that connects the input values to the output values.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Use the discovered rule to determine:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="i">
                        <li><p><m>f(50)</m></p></li>
                        <li><p><m>f(88)</m></p></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Explain your reasoning for the function rule you discovered.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Compare your function rule with those of your classmates. 
                    Explain how you discovered the relationship between the inputs and outputs. 
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>

    </activity>
    
    <definition xml:id="def-function-notation">
        <statement>
            <p>
                A <term>function</term> <m>f</m> is a rule that assigns exactly one output value to each input value. 
                If the function maps elements from a set <m>A</m> to a set <m>B</m>, we write
            </p>

            
            <p>
                <me>f: A \rightarrow B</me>
            </p>

            <p>
                which is read as “<q>a function from <m>A</m> to <m>B</m></q>.” 
                The set <m>A</m> is called the <term>domain</term>, while the set <m>B</m> is called the 
                <term>co-domain</term>. The collection of all actual outputs produced by the function is called the 
                <term>range</term> or <term>image</term> of the function.
            </p>

            <p>
                An element from the domain is called an <term>argument</term> or <term>input value</term>. 
                If <m>x \in A</m>, then the output produced by the function is written as <m>f(x)</m>, 
                which is read as “<q>f of x</q>.” The value <m>f(x)</m> is called the 
                <term>function value</term>, <term>image</term>, or <term>output</term>.
            </p>

            <p>
                Since a function assigns exactly one output to each input, two different outputs cannot come from the same input. 
                However, different inputs may produce the same output.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
        Function notation provides a simple and organized way of describing how a function works. 
        The letter naming the function, such as <m>f</m>, tells us which rule is being used, while the expression inside the parentheses represents the input value being substituted into the rule.
    </p>

    <p>
        You can think of a function as a machine: an input value is placed into the function, the rule performs an operation, and a single output value is produced.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="fig-function-machine-notation">
        <caption>The input-output process of a function using function notation.</caption>
        <image xml:id="img-function-machine" width="60%">
            <latex-image>
                \begin{tikzpicture}[&gt;=stealth, font=\sffamily]

                    % Input arrow
                    \draw[-&gt;, ultra thick, blue!80!black] (-4,0) -- (-1.8,0);
                    \node[align=center] at (-3,0.9)
                    {\textbf{Input}\\$x \in A$};

                    % Function box
                    \draw[thick, rounded corners=10pt, fill=blue!10]
                    (-1.8,-1.5) rectangle (1.8,1.5);

                    \node[align=center] at (0,0)
                    {\textbf{Function}\\$f$};

                    % Output arrow
                    \draw[-&gt;, ultra thick, orange!80!black] (1.8,0) -- (4,0);

                    \node[align=center] at (3,0.9)
                    {\textbf{Output}\\$f(x) \in B$};

                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
        </image>
    </figure>

    <p>
        The usefulness of function notation becomes clearer when we evaluate functions. 
        To evaluate a function, we replace the input variable with a given value or expression and simplify the result.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="ex-eval-positive">

        <statement>
            <p>
                Given the function <m>f(x)=4x-7</m>, determine <m>f(3)</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p>
                Replace every occurrence of <m>x</m> with <m>3</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
                <me>f(3)=4(3)-7</me>
                <me>f(3)=12-7</me>
                <me>f(3)=5</me>
            </p>

            <p>
                Therefore, the function value corresponding to the input <m>3</m> is <m>5</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-eval-negative">

        <statement>
            <p>
                Given <m>g(t)=t^2+2t</m>, evaluate <m>g(-4)</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p>
                Substitute <m>-4</m> for every occurrence of <m>t</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
                <me>g(-4)=(-4)^2+2(-4)</me>
                <me>g(-4)=16-8</me>
                <me>g(-4)=8</me>
            </p>

            <p>
                Hence, <m>g(-4)=8</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-eval-expression">
        <statement>
            <p>
                If <m>h(x)=5x+1</m>, determine <m>h(a+3)</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p>
                The input can also be an algebraic expression. 
                Replace <m>x</m> with <m>a+3</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
                <me>h(a+3)=5(a+3)+1</me>
                <me>h(a+3)=5a+15+1</me>
                <me>h(a+3)=5a+16</me>
            </p>

            <p>
                Therefore, <m>h(a+3)=5a+16</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-function-notation-word">
        <statement>
            <p>
                A taxi company charges a fixed fee of <m>200</m> shillings and an additional 
                <m>50</m> shillings per kilometre travelled. The total fare is given by
            </p>

            <p>
                <me>F(k)=50k+200</me>
            </p>

            <p>
                where <m>k</m> represents the number of kilometres travelled. Find <m>F(6)</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p>
                Substitute <m>6</m> for <m>k</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
                <me>F(6)=50(6)+200</me>
                <me>F(6)=300+200</me>
                <me>F(6)=500</me>
            </p>

            <p>
                Therefore, the cost of travelling <m>6</m> kilometres is 
                <m>500</m> shillings.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <exercises xml:id="exercises-function-notation">
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    If <m>f(x)=4x-1</m>, determine <m>f(5)</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>

            <answer>
                <p><m>19</m></p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Given <m>g(x)=x^2+2x</m>, evaluate <m>g(-3)</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>

            <answer>
                <p><m>3</m></p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Let <m>h(t)=3t+7</m>. Find <m>h(0)</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>

            <answer>
                <p><m>7</m></p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    If <m>p(x)=\frac{x-4}{2}</m>, determine <m>p(10)</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>

            <answer>
                <p><m>3</m></p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Given <m>m(x)=2x^2-3</m>, evaluate <m>m(-2)</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>

            <answer>
                <p><m>5</m></p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Let <m>f(x)=5x+2</m>. Determine <m>f(a)</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>

            <answer>
                <p><m>5a+2</m></p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    If <m>g(x)=3x-4</m>, find <m>g(k+2)</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>

            <answer>
                <p><m>3k+2</m></p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Given <m>h(x)=x^2+1</m>, determine <m>h(2a)</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>

            <answer>
                <p><m>4a^2+1</m></p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A mobile network charges <m>10</m> shillings per minute for a call and a fixed connection fee of <m>5</m> shillings. 
                    The total cost is given by <m>C(t)=10t+5</m>, where <m>t</m> is the number of minutes. Find <m>C(8)</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>

            <answer>
                <p><m>85</m></p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A farmer sells eggs at <m>15</m> shillings each. If the total amount earned is represented by 
                    <m>E(n)=15n</m>, where <m>n</m> is the number of eggs sold, determine <m>E(24)</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>

            <answer>
                <p><m>360</m></p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>


    </exercises>


</section>
